    "narrative": "The Zurich Zebras enter today\u2019s slate leaning heavily on **Trea Turner** and **Colt Keith** as the anchors of the offensive output. **Trea Turner** is our top-rated play with a 65.80 efficiency score, buoyed by a favorable wind-out condition and a prime leadoff spot against Cabrera. His ability to impact the scarcest category, stolen bases, remains our primary driver here. Complementing him is **Colt Keith**, whose score of 63.01 benefits from a favorable matchup against Sproat and a high-leverage #3 spot in the order. Similarly, **Kyle Schwarber** (62.48) is a mandatory start; his elite xwOBA profile coupled with the same wind-out factors hitting Cabrera make him a high-floor producer despite the moderate SP_xERA of 3.72.\n\nOur strategy for the rest of the lineup is one of risk mitigation against top-tier arms. **Gary Sanchez** faces a daunting matchup against the elite Skubal (2.71 xERA); while his 45.85 score keeps him in the starting lineup, his performance will be capped by the skill disparity of the opposing starter. We are closely monitoring the status of **Josh Smith**, currently projected in the #8 hole; should his lineup spot shift lower, he risks dipping below our critical 40.0 efficiency floor. The most difficult bench decision involved **Carson Benge**, who finished at 38.70. While he offers some platoon upside, the combination of a bottom-of-the-order assignment and a difficult matchup against Ryan forced us to stick to the bench to preserve our game caps. We continue to track the availability of **Yordan Alvarez**, **Junior Caminero**, and **Pete Crow-Armstrong**, as their absence from the active rotation today creates a significant void in our power and speed production. Finally, **Hyeseong Kim** remains a situational play; while his score of 41.34 is marginal, the 100% stolen base opportunity rate against the battery he faces keeps him ahead of the bench options, even with the anchor of an #8 batting position.",
